## What it does

Watches your screen on a configurable poll interval. Each cycle it captures a
screenshot, asks Claude to check whether a Codex confirmation pop-up is visible,
and clicks the Accept button if one is found. It stops when Codex reports
completion or the maximum cycle count is reached.

## Setup

Install the required system dependencies:

```bash
pip install pyautogui Pillow
```

On Linux you may also need:

```bash
sudo apt-get install scrot python3-tk python3-dev
```

Set your Anthropic API key:

```bash
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="sk-ant-..."
```

## Usage

```bash
# Dry run — prints the plan without touching the screen
python workflow.py

# Live run
python -c "
from workflow import run
result = run({'dry_run': False, 'config': {'poll_interval_seconds': 3}})
print(result)
"
```

Or via the Hermes CLI:

```bash
hermes factory dry-run {{ slug }}
hermes factory enable  {{ slug }}
```

## Configuration

Pass a `config` dict to `run()`:

| Key | Default | Description |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `poll_interval_seconds` | `3` | Seconds between screenshots |
| `max_iterations` | `300` | Maximum polling cycles (~15 min at 3 s) |

## Safety

- Denied: keyboard input, shell execution, file writes, package installation.
- Only clicks buttons explicitly labelled Accept / Confirm / OK / Yes / Apply /
  Continue / Approve / Allow on a visible Codex dialog.
- Requires explicit `enabled: true` before the live path is reachable.

